    <p>These three beacons use the Cospas-Sarsat network.  When you turn one on:</p>
    <ul>
        <li>The GPS receiver activates and tries to get your position from GPS satellites</li>
        <br/>
        <li>The 406 MHz beacon activates, transmitting at 5W signal into space to be received by two different types of satellites:</li>
        <br/>
        <ul>
            <li>LEOSAR (low earth orbit search and rescue) satellites cover the entire globe periodically.  As soon as one is in range, it receives your signal (which includes GPS information if you have a GPS lock).  These satellites are moving, so they can use doppler shift techniques to calculate your location in a second way (in case you can't get a GPS lock).</li>
            <br/>
            <li>GEOSAR (geostationary search and rescue) satellites with a much higher orbit receive your signal and rebroadcast.  These have limited coverage in polar regions (>70 degrees latitude) but from the rest of the planet should always be visible.</li>
        </ul>
        <br/>
        <li>Assuming you have <strong>registered</strong> your beacon, the authorities will determine who you are based on your beacon ID and begin to coordinate a rescue.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
    This picture (from <a href="https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:New_C-S_System_Overview.jpg">here</a>) gives a simple outline of the system:
    <%= image_tag("cospas-sarsat.jpg", :class => "img-responsive") %>
        <br/>
    This satellite network has the longest track record of successful rescues (<a href="https://www.cospas-sarsat.int/en/search-and-rescue/statistics">almost 40,000 people rescued since its creation</a>).
    It was originally set up by international agreement--that means no private ownership.  If you buy one of these beacons, make sure to register! (information will come with your beacon.  In the US, for example you will register with <a href="http://www.sarsat.noaa.gov/">NOAA</a>)
    </p>
